We currently have this:
~~~
:status = 200
content-type = application/pvd+json
content-length = 135

{
  "identifier": "proxy.example.org.",
  "expires": "2023-06-23T06:00:00Z",
  "prefixes": [],
  "proxies": [
    {
      "protocol": "http-connect",
      "proxy": "proxy.example.org:80"
    },
    {
      "protocol": "connect-udp",
      "proxy": "https://proxy.example.org/masque{?target_host,target_port}",
      "match": [{
        domains: [ "*.internal.example.org" ]
      }]
    }
  ]
}
~~~

That isn't easy to make both proxies have the same match domains.

One option we discussed and liked is having the match list be separate from proxy list; add some identifier to the proxy dictionary; and have the match rules refer to which proxies they apply to.

~~~
:status = 200
content-type = application/pvd+json
content-length = 135

{
  "identifier": "proxy.example.org.",
  "expires": "2023-06-23T06:00:00Z",
  "prefixes": [],
  "proxies": [
    {
      "identifier": "All Proxy",
      "protocol": "http-connect",
      "proxy": "all-proxy.example.org:80",
    },
    {
      "identifier": "TCP Proxy"
      "protocol": "http-connect",
      "proxy": "proxy.example.org:80",
      "mandatory": [ "auth" ],
      "auth": "basic"
    },
    {
      "identifier": "UDP Proxy"
      "protocol": "connect-udp",
      "proxy": "https://proxy.example.org/masque{?target_host,target_port}",
    }
  ]
  "matchProxies": [ {
      "proxies": [ "All Proxy" ]
  },{
      "proxies": [ "TCP Proxy", "UDP Proxy" ],
      "domains": [ "*.internal.example.org" ],
      "ports": [ 80, 443 ]
  }, {
      "proxies": [ "TCP Proxy" ],
      "domains": [ "*.internal.example.org" ],
      "ports": [ 22 ],
      "proprietaryKey": "foobar" // Match rule only applies if you understand "proprietaryKey"
  }]
  "excludeProxies": [{
      "proxies": [ "TCP Proxy", "UDP Proxy" ],
      "domains": [ "foo.internal.example.org" ]
  }]
}
~~~

Other alternatives below:
~~~
